efter 1640","1549":"1549","AFT 1460":"efter 1460","Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Jórvík, England","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1420–after 1640":"1420–na 1640","1420–1640":"1420–1640","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1425–1460":"1425–1460","1460–1518":"1460–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1620":"1620","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1640":"1640","1518":"1518","after 1640":"na 1640","1549":"1549","AFT 1460":"na 1460","Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Foolow, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1420–after 1640":"1420–after 1640","1420–1640":"1420–1640","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1425–1460":"1425–1460","1460–1518":"1460–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1620":"1620","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1640":"1640","1518":"1518","after 1640":"after 1640","1549":"1549","AFT 1460":"after 1460","Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hancock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Hann   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>, which was commonly added to personal names (see   Cocke  ).","Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hanecoc</i> ‘winkle, periwinkle’ (a type of shellfish), probably a metonymic occupational name for someone who gathered and sold shellfish.","History: Thomas Hancock, the uncle of Declaration of Independence signatory John Hancock (1736/7–93), was among the foremost of 18th-century American businessmen. He was a descendant of Nathaniel Hancock, who was known to have been in Cambridge, MA, as early as 1634. Born in Braintree, MA, John Hancock was president of the Second Continental Congress and the first governor of the state of MA."],"variants":[{"name":"Hancox","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Handcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock   with intrusive <i>-d-</i>."]},{"name":"Hann","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a shortened pet form of the personal name <i>Johann</i> (see   John  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hann</i>, commonly a pet form of <i>Henry</i> (Middle English <i>Hanry</i>). <i>Hann</i> could also be a rhyming pet form of Randolph (Middle English <i>Randal</i>, shortened to <i>Ran</i> or <i>Rand</i>). <i>Han</i> was also a pet form of <i>Joh(a)n</i> in Middle Dutch, and it is possible that this usage was brought to England by Flemings after the Norman Conquest, but no evidence has yet been found that it was similarly used in Middle English. See   Henry   and   Randall  , and compare   Hankin  ,   Hancock  , and   Hanks  .","English: variant of   Ann   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Benjamin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the youngest of the twelve sons of Jacob. His mother Rachel died in giving birth to him, and in her last moments she named him <i>Benoni</i>, meaning ‘son of my sorrow’. His father, however, did not wish him to bear such an ill-omened name, and renamed him <i>Benyamin</i> (Genesis 35:16–18; 42:4). This means either ‘son of the right hand’ or more likely ‘son of the south’ (Hebrew <i>yamin</i> can also mean ‘south’), since Benjamin was the only child of Jacob born in Canaan and not in Mesopotamia to the north. Another tradition is that the second element of the name is a variant of the Hebrew plural noun <i>yamim</i>, which means ‘days’ but is used idiomatically to mean ‘year’ or ‘years’. The name would then mean ‘son of (my) old age’ and refer to the fact that Benjamin was Jacob's youngest child. In the Middle Ages the name was often given to sons whose mothers had died in childbirth. Today it has no such unfortunate associations and it grew enormously in popularity following the release of the film The Graduate (  1967 ), in which  Dustin Hoffman  played the role of  Benjamin Braddock . It is used in Scotland as an Anglicized form of Gaelic Beathan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":129,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":138,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":180,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":200,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When SIR Benjamin Hancock was born in 1420, in Bradford, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Hancock, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Witt, was 21. He married Joan Lawerence in 1445, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1420–after 1640":"1420–pärast 1640","1420–1640":"1420–1640","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1425–1460":"1425–1460","1460–1518":"1460–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1620":"1620","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1640":"1640","1518":"1518","after 1640":"pärast 1640","1549":"1549","AFT 1460":"pärast 1460","Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Foolow, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1420–after 1640":"1420–1640 jälkeen","1420–1640":"1420–1640","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1425–1460":"1425–1460","1460–1518":"1460–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1460":"1460","1558":"1558","1425":"1425","1435":"1435","1600":"1600","1445":"1445","1620":"1620","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1640":"1640","1518":"1518","after 1640":"1640 jälkeen","1549":"1549","AFT 1460":"1460 jälkeen","Foolow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Foolow, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England","Chesterfield, Der